1. cs.IT (Information Theory) - The paper deals with the problem of detecting a random walk on a graph based on observations of the graph nodes. It uses concepts from information theory such as entropy and error exponent to characterize detection performance. 
2. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper is concerned with detecting random walks on graphs, which is a topic related to social and information networks. 
3. cs.LG (Machine Learning) - The paper uses optimization techniques to compute a lower bound on the error exponent, which is a problem commonly encountered in machine learning. 
4. cs.SY (Systems and Control) - The paper deals with the problem of detecting a random walk on a graph, which can be seen as a control problem. 
5. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) - The paper uses mathematical concepts such as Markov types and Lyapunov exponents to derive the lower bound on the error exponent, which are related to data structures and algorithms.
